# OSPlus PowerShell conventions

OSPlus's PowerShell is **procedural automation only** — build, deploy, setup, packaging. There are no long-running PS services. All scripts run on Windows and target Windows + (via `ssh`/`scp`) the OCI Ubuntu VM.

For cross-cutting (logging format, comment policy), see `code-conventions.mdc`.

## `$ErrorActionPreference = "Stop"` at the top

Every non-trivial script (more than ~10 lines) starts with:

```powershell
$ErrorActionPreference = "Stop"
```

PowerShell's default `Continue` silently swallows errors from PS-native cmdlets. `Stop` makes them throw. **Without this, "successful" runs can leave half-built artifacts.**

The exception: when calling external tools that emit informational lines on stderr (npm, esbuild, postject), save+restore around the call:

```powershell
$prevPref = $ErrorActionPreference
$ErrorActionPreference = "Continue"
try {
    & npm install --silent 2>&1 | Where-Object { $_ -notmatch "^npm warn" }
    # ... more noisy commands ...
} finally {
    $ErrorActionPreference = $prevPref
}
```

## `$LASTEXITCODE` is the external-command footgun

**`$ErrorActionPreference = "Stop"` does NOT trip on `$LASTEXITCODE` from external commands.** A `& git push` that fails with exit 1 will silently continue unless you explicitly check.

Use `Invoke-External` from `tools/_lib.ps1`:

```powershell
. "$PSScriptRoot\tools\_lib.ps1"

Invoke-External "scp uploading deploy/" {
    & scp -i $key -r ./deploy "$user@$host:/tmp/"
}
```

Or, if you can't use the helper for some reason, write the explicit check:

```powershell
& <command> ...
if ($LASTEXITCODE -ne 0) { throw "<label> failed (exit code: $LASTEXITCODE)" }
```

Never call an external command without one of these patterns. The label in the throw message is what makes failures diagnosable two months later.

## Use `tools/_lib.ps1` helpers, don't reinvent

The shared logging helpers live in `tools/_lib.ps1`:

| Helper | Visual | Use for |
|---|---|---|
| `Write-Step "msg"` | `==> msg` (cyan) | Major phase header. Each section of a multi-step script gets one. |
| `Write-Ok "msg"` | `    [ok] msg` (green) | Success / completion of a step. |
| `Write-Warn2 "msg"` | `    [!] msg` (yellow) | Non-fatal warning. |
| `Write-Fail "msg"` | `    [fail] msg` (red) | Failure. Caller decides whether to `throw` or `exit 1`. |

(`Write-Warn2` is named that way to avoid colliding with PS's built-in `Write-Warning`, which respects `$WarningPreference` and has different semantics.)

Bootstrap-specific helpers (`Get-LatestRelease`, `Find-ReleaseAsset`, `Download-Release`, `Expand-To`) live in `tools/setup/_lib.ps1`, which dot-sources `tools/_lib.ps1` so setup scripts get both.

**Dot-source paths from common locations:**

| Script location | Dot-source line |
|---|---|
| Project root (`build_dist.ps1`, `deploy.ps1`) | `. "$PSScriptRoot\tools\_lib.ps1"` |
| One-level subfolder (`ue-assets/`) | `. "$PSScriptRoot\..\tools\_lib.ps1"` |
| Two-level subfolder (`server/deploy/`) | `. "$PSScriptRoot\..\..\tools\_lib.ps1"` |
| `tools/setup/` | `. "$PSScriptRoot\_lib.ps1"` (gets both libs transitively) |

ASCII banners and per-line context info (e.g. printing the SSH key path so the user can verify it before connecting) can stay as raw `Write-Host` — the helpers are for *step status*, not all output.

## Encoding — be explicit, always

PowerShell's default text encoding is historically a moving target (PS5: UTF-16-LE-with-BOM; PS7: UTF-8 no BOM). **Never trust the default for files consumed by other tools.** Pick one explicitly:

- Tool input files (UnrealPak response files, sed scripts, anything Unix tools read):
  ```powershell
  $lines | Out-File -FilePath $f -Encoding ascii
  ```
- Clean UTF-8 without BOM (config files, JSON consumed by Node):
  ```powershell
  [System.IO.File]::WriteAllText($path, $content)
  ```
- Anything else where a human reads it: `Out-File -Encoding utf8` is fine.

The classic failure mode: `$lines | Out-File $response_file` writes UTF-16, UnrealPak rejects the whole file with a cryptic error, you spend an hour wondering why.

## Line endings — `.gitattributes` first, sed second

Files consumed on Linux (`*.sh`, `*.service`, `Caddyfile`) must be LF. The repo's `.gitattributes` enforces this on commit/checkout. **But:** files edited with non-Git-aware tools (e.g. opened in Notepad and re-saved) can still drift to CRLF.

Belt-and-suspenders: scripts that ship files to Linux also normalize on the remote. Pattern from `server/deploy/ship.ps1`:

```powershell
Invoke-External "line-ending normalization" {
    & ssh @sshArgs "find $RemoteStaging/server -type f \( -name '*.sh' -o -name '*.service' -o -name 'Caddyfile' \) -exec sed -i 's/\r`$//' {} +"
}
```

(Note the backtick-escaped `` `$ `` so PS doesn't interpolate the `$` before sending to bash.)

See `docs/learnings/oci-relay-deploy-gotchas.md` for the full failure-mode story.

## Hardcoded `F:\` paths — known scope debt, not a pattern to copy

Production scripts (`build_dist.ps1`, `package_logicmod.ps1`, `package_pak.ps1`, `deploy.ps1`) hardcode `F:\Omegamod\OmegaStonkers 5.1\`, `F:\UE510\`, `F:\SteamLibrary\...`. This is technically wrong (non-portable across machines/developers) and pragmatically acceptable today because:

- There is one developer, one machine, one toolchain layout.
- Game install + UE source build paths are external to the repo and not parameterizable without significant complexity.
- Adding env-var indirection now would be a YAGNI tax with no payoff for the only consumer.

**Rules:**

1. If you add a new hardcoded `F:\` path: fail loudly with an actionable error if it doesn't exist (`Write-Fail "X not found at $path; expected after step Y"`). Don't let the user discover the bad path 5 minutes into a build.
2. Don't propagate the pattern to *new* tooling that has any chance of being run by anyone else (e.g. a contributor onboarding script). For those, use a config file or env vars from the start.
3. When a second developer joins or the user's machine layout changes: parameterize as a `chore/` branch, don't try to fix it in-line during another change.

## Naming

| Kind | Convention | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| Constants / paths | `$UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` | `$ROOT`, `$DIST`, `$UNREALPAK`, `$LOGICMODS_DIR` |
| Transient variables | `$camelCase` | `$serverDir`, `$luaCount`, `$prevPref` |
| Functions | `Verb-Noun` PascalCase (PS standard) | `Write-Step`, `Get-LatestRelease`, `Invoke-External` |
| Script parameters | PascalCase via `param()` | `$VmHost`, `$KeyPath`, `$RemoteStaging` |

## CmdletBinding for parameterized scripts

Scripts that take parameters use `[CmdletBinding()]` + `param()`:

```powershell
[CmdletBinding()]
param(
    [string] $VmHost = "136.248.104.200",
    [string] $User    = "ubuntu",
    [string] $KeyPath = "$env:USERPROFILE\.ssh\osplus_oci.key"
)
```

This gives `-Verbose`, `-Debug`, `-ErrorAction`, etc. for free, and makes `Get-Help script.ps1` work properly.

Trivial scripts with no parameters don't need `[CmdletBinding()]`.

## What is NOT in scope of this rule

- **Indentation, brace style, line length** — formatter territory.
- **Hardcoded paths beyond the policy above** — case-by-case judgment.
- **Pester / unit testing PowerShell** — no test infrastructure exists yet.
- **Cross-platform PS (running on Linux/macOS)** — explicitly out of scope; OSPlus PS is Windows-only.
